            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this CCTV hardware calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed for security engineers, integrators, and
                IT teams who need a quick, transparent way to estimate
                <strong>storage, bandwidth, and NVR/server hardware</strong> for
                video surveillance projects. Unlike many vendor tools, all
                assumptions are visible and adjustable.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Bitrate estimation model</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator starts from a typical bitrate for each
                combination of <strong>resolution</strong>,
                <strong>codec</strong>, and <strong>scene complexity</strong>,
                then scales it by frame rate and duty cycle.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Base bitrate per camera</strong> (Mbps) is chosen from
                  a table, then:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{bitrate}_\text{camera} = \text{base} \times
                  \frac{\text{fps}}{15} \times \frac{\text{duty cycle}}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Example: 1080p, H.265, medium scene, 15 fps, 100% duty → base
                  ≈ 2.5 Mbps.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Storage calculation</h3>
              <p>
                Once we know the effective bitrate per camera, we convert it to
                daily and total storage for the chosen retention period.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{storage}_\text{per camera (GB)} =
                  \frac{\text{bitrate}_\text{camera} \times 10^6}{8} \times
                  \text{hours/day} \times 3600 \times \text{retention days} \div
                  10^9 \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{total usable storage} = \text{storage}_\text{per
                  camera} \times \text{number of cameras} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{raw storage} = \text{total usable} \times (1 +
                  \text{safety margin}) \times \text{RAID overhead factor} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The <strong>safety margin</strong> (e.g. 25%) accounts for
                bitrate variation, firmware changes, and future cameras. The
                <strong>RAID overhead factor</strong> approximates how much
                extra raw capacity is needed to achieve the usable capacity:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>None / JBOD: factor ≈ 1.00</li>
                <li>RAID 1: factor ≈ 2.00 (mirroring)</li>
                <li>
                  RAID 5: factor ≈ 1.20 (depends on disk count; this is a
                  planning average)
                </li>
                <li>RAID 6: factor ≈ 1.33</li>
                <li>RAID 10: factor ≈ 2.00</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Bandwidth and network sizing</h3>
              <p>
                The tool reports both <strong>recording bitrate</strong> (toward
                the NVR) and <strong>live-view bitrate</strong> (toward
                clients). In many deployments, live view uses a lower-resolution
                substream; here we assume the same stream for simplicity, so:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{total recording bitrate} =
                  \text{bitrate}_\text{camera} \times \text{number of cameras}
                  \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  For remote clients, we suggest a
                  <strong>per-client uplink</strong> based on a handful of
                  simultaneous streams (e.g. 4 cameras at once).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. NVR / server hardware recommendations</h3>
              <p>
                Hardware sizing is highly vendor-dependent, but you need a
                starting point. This calculator uses conservative rules of
                thumb:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Server count</strong>: total cameras ÷ max cameras per
                  server (rounded up).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>CPU class</strong>: based on cameras per server and
                  total bitrate (e.g. entry, mid-range, high-end).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>CPU cores</strong>: baseline of 4 cores per server
                  plus extra cores per 50 Mbps of recording load.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>RAM</strong>: 8 GB minimum, plus 0.5–1 GB per 10
                  cameras.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Drive bays</strong>: raw storage per server ÷ planned
                  drive size, rounded up.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These values are intentionally rounded and conservative. Always
                cross-check with your VMS vendor’s official hardware guidelines
                and perform soak testing before going to production.
              </p>

              <h2>Best practices for CCTV storage and hardware planning</h2>
              <h3>Use motion-based recording where appropriate</h3>
              <p>
                Continuous 24/7 recording at full frame rate can quickly explode
                storage requirements. For many scenes, motion-based recording
                with a reasonable pre/post buffer can cut storage by 40–70%
                without losing important events. Use the
                <strong>Recording duty cycle</strong> field to simulate this.
              </p>

              <h3>Separate recording and live-view workloads</h3>
              <p>
                In larger systems, it’s common to dedicate some servers to
                recording and others to live viewing and analytics. This
                calculator assumes a combined workload, but you can run it twice
                with different parameters (e.g. lower fps for recording, higher
                for live view) to size each tier separately.
              </p>

              <h3>Plan for growth</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Leave spare drive bays and network capacity for future
                  cameras.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use the safety margin slider to see how much extra storage is
                  reasonable.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Consider higher-capacity disks or expansion shelves for large
                  sites.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Validate with real-world tests</h3>
              <p>
                Vendor calculators (Luxriot, AxxonSoft, Genetec, etc.) are
                useful, but they often hide their assumptions. Use this tool to
                get a transparent baseline, then validate with:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Short-term test recordings on representative cameras and
                  scenes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Monitoring actual bitrate and disk usage over several days.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Stress tests with peak client connections and analytics
                  enabled.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Why do my vendor tools give different numbers?</h3>
              <p>
                Different tools use different bitrate tables, compression
                assumptions, and overhead factors. Some assume aggressive
                compression (e.g. H.265+), others assume worst-case scenes. This
                calculator aims for realistic, slightly conservative values that
                you can adjust via frame rate, duty cycle, and safety margin.
              </p>

              <h3>How many days of retention should I choose?</h3>
              <p>
                Common values are 7, 14, 30, 60, or 90 days, depending on
                regulation, risk profile, and budget. Some industries (e.g.
                banking, critical infrastructure) may require 180 days or more.
                Always check local laws and your organization’s policy.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I use RAID 5, RAID 6, or RAID 10?</h3>
              <p>
                For large disks (10 TB+), RAID 6 or RAID 10 is generally
                preferred because rebuild times are long and the risk of a
                second disk failure is higher. RAID 5 is more space-efficient
                but less resilient. Many modern NVRs also support
                file-system-level redundancy (e.g. ZFS) which changes the
                trade-offs.
              </p>
